Not sure if it is a separate issue or duplicate of #21097, as it produce the same error but with different code pattern.

**Version Used**: 15.5.3, 15.5.4

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```cs
    public class Test
    {
        public void TestIt(object o1, object o2)
        {
            var test = o1 as Test;
            if (test != null || o2 != null)
            {
                var o3 = test ?? o2;
            }
        }
    }
```
**Expected Behavior**:
no fix proposal

**Actual Behavior**:
```cs
    public class Test
    {
        public void TestIt(object o1, object o2)
        {
            if (o1 is Test test || o2 != null)
            {
                // CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'test'
                var o3 = test ?? o2;
            }
        }
    }
```

Testcase: SpillingByrefCall_Spilling

C# class introduces ref methods
```C#
using System;

public class TestClass
{
    int x = 0;

    public ref int Save(int y)
    {
        x = y;
        return ref x;
    }

    public void Write(ref int y)
    {
        Console.WriteLine(y);
    }

    public void Write(ref int y, int z)
    {
        Console.WriteLine(y);
    }
}
```

VB test code (references the above code):
```VB
Imports System.Threading.Tasks

Module Module1

    Sub Main()
        TestMethod().Wait()
    End Sub

    Async Function TestMethod() As Task
        Dim inst = New TestClass

        ' ERROR?
        ' currently `ref` is spilled 'by-value' and assert fires.
        inst.Write(inst.Save(Await Task.FromResult(30)), inst.Save(Await Task.FromResult(33)))
    End Function

End Module
```

Expected: 
- not sure. C# gives an error. Possibly VB should as well

Actual:
- compiler asserts. If ignored, the `ref` argument is spilled by-value

It might actually be ok in VB to spill by-value. Not sure. 
In any case there should not be asserts.

Also note - changing current behavior (ignoring the assert) might be a compat concern. This behavior existed since the last release.

The first code sample is an existing test, and arguably behaves correctly (the async local function is only guaranteed to execute until the first await is reached).

The second code sample shows that this behavior doesn't change when calling the local function with await.

The third code sample shows that adding a finally inside the local function affects the definite assignment of `y`, but it's hard to see why.

Tagging @AlekseyTs @agocke @gafter 

Relates to my recent PR on async using (https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/23961).

```C#
using System.Threading.Tasks;
class C
{
    public static void M2()
    {
        int a=0, x, y, z;
        L1();
        a++;
        x++;
        y++; // error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'y'
        z++; // error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'z'

        async void L1()
        {
            x = 0;
            await Task.CompletedTask;
            y = 0;
        }
    }
}
```

```C#
using System.Threading.Tasks;
class C
{
    public static async Task M2()
    {
        int a=0, x, y, z;
        await L1(); // adding await doesn't affect the warnings (is that correct?)
        a++;
        x++;
        y++; // error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'y'
        z++; // error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'z'

        async Task L1()
        {
            x = 0;
            await Task.CompletedTask;
            y = 0;
        }
    }
}
```

```C#
using System.Threading.Tasks;
class C
{
    public static void M2()
    {
        int a=0, x, y, z;
        L1();
        a++;
        x++;
        y++; // no error anymore. That seems wrong
        z++; // error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'z'

        async void L1()
        {
            try
            {
            	x = 0;
            	await Task.CompletedTask;
            }
            finally
            {
                y = 0; // assigning y in finally removes the error on y above 
            }
        }
    }
}
```

